<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_dictionary` row that
    declares the `assigned_agent` Reference field on the `x_casemgmt_case`
    custom table inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim):
        Field            Type                    Constraints
        assigned_agent   Reference -> sys_user   Optional; must be member of assigned_group

    THIS FIELD IS A LOAD-BEARING PILLAR OF THE STATE-MACHINE GATE for
    Open -> In Progress AND of the role-based authorization model. Per
    AAP Section 0.5.5 the transition matrix's second non-trivial gate is:

        From   To           Required condition                                    Blocking-error behavior
        Open   In Progress  assigned_agent populated AND member of assigned_group Surface form-level error

    The "Optional" qualifier from AAP Section 0.5.7 is a strict
    DICTIONARY-LEVEL declaration: a Draft or Open case MUST be permitted
    to exist without an assigned_agent. This is what enables the
    unauthenticated portal-submission endpoint
    (../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_casemgmt_case_submit.xml) to land
    new portal-submitted cases in Draft status without requiring the
    anonymous external requester to know about, much less choose, an
    internal ServiceNow user. It also reflects the standard intake
    pattern: case_manager users assign the responsible group during
    Draft -> Open promotion, and only later (during Open -> In Progress)
    is an individual agent picked up from within that group. The
    dictionary entry therefore declares `<mandatory>false</mandatory>`,
    and the Open -> In Progress gate is enforced by the Flow Designer
    subflow at ../flows/sub_flows/validate_inprogress_transition.xml.
    Setting `<mandatory>true</mandatory>` here would block save of
    Draft and Open cases without an agent, which directly contradicts
    AAP Section 0.5.7's enumerated state list (Draft and Open are both
    allowed prior to In Progress) and AAP Section 0.5.1's portal-
    submission contract ("the submission page writes a new
    x_casemgmt_case record with status = Draft and returns the auto-
    numbered number").

    Beyond the Open -> In Progress gate, this field participates in
    THREE other critical mechanisms (AAP Sections 0.4.1, 0.5.6):

      1. AGENT MEMBERSHIP VALIDATION
         (../business_rules/x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml)
         Per AAP Section 0.5.7: "assigned_agent | Reference -> sys_user |
         Optional; must be member of assigned_group". When a manager or
         agent populates assigned_agent, a before-update business rule
         on the parent x_casemgmt_case table verifies the chosen sys_user
         is a direct or indirect member of the chosen assigned_group via
         the OOB `sys_user_grmember` join table. If the agent is NOT a
         member, the rule calls current.setAbortAction(true) and surfaces
         a form-level blocking error. This validation cannot be expressed
         at the dictionary level (a reference qualifier could only filter
         the picker, not block out-of-band Table-API or scripted REST
         updates), so it lives in the business-rule layer alongside the
         identical guard inside the Flow Designer subflow.

      2. FIELD-LEVEL ACL (write restricted to case_manager and the
         currently-assigned case_agent)
         (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml)
         Per AAP Section 0.5.6: "ACLs MUST be defined at table level AND
         field level for sensitive fields (assigned_group, assigned_agent)."
         The field-level ACL restricts write access to:
           a) The x_casemgmt_case_manager role (who may freely re-assign
              cases between agents within an assigned_group), AND
           b) The x_casemgmt_case_agent role IF the current user IS the
              currently-assigned agent (so an agent may RE-assign to a
              different agent during handoff, but a case_agent who is
              NOT the assignee cannot poach the assignment).
         The dictionary entry's own `<write_roles/>` element below is
         intentionally empty so that the dedicated ACL system (not the
         dictionary's role lists) governs write access. This is the
         standard ServiceNow pattern for fine-grained field protection.

      3. "ASSIGNED ONLY" READ/WRITE ACL CONDITION FOR case_agent
         (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned.xml,
          ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_agent_assigned.xml)
         Per AAP Section 0.5.6: "'Assigned only' = cases where
         assigned_agent = current user OR assigned_group contains current
         user." The table-level read/write ACLs for case_agent encode
         this condition as a scripted ACL expression that compares
         current.assigned_agent against gs.getUserID() OR queries
         sys_user_grmember for membership in current.assigned_group.
         This field is therefore one of the TWO gates (alongside
         assigned_group) that determine the visible case set for any
         agent. The "My Open Cases" report in
         ../reports/x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml further narrows the list
         to (assigned_agent = javascript:gs.getUserID()) AND
         (status NOT IN [Resolved, Closed]) - making this field central
         to the agent's daily workspace dashboard.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java line 892-899:
            public String getAssigneeLdapId()
            {
                return getParticipants().stream().filter(
                    p -> CaseFileConstants.ASSIGNEE.equals(p.getParticipantType())
                ) ...
            }
        ArkCase did NOT have a first-class `assignee` JPA column on
        `acm_case_file`. Instead, the assignee was derived at runtime
        from the participants collection by filtering for participants
        whose `participantType` equaled the constant
        `CaseFileConstants.ASSIGNEE`, then projecting the
        `participantLdapId` (a free-form String username from the OpenLDAP
        directory backing ArkCase). Several derived getters
        (`getAssigneeLdapId()`, `getAssigneeGroup()`, `getAssigneeGroupId()`,
        `getAssigneeFullName()`, `getAssigneeTitle()`, `getAssigneePhone()`)
        materialised the assignee as transient String fields each time
        they were called, with no referential integrity to any user table.
        This was a known pain point: the LDAP id could be misspelled,
        could refer to a deactivated user, or could fail to map to a
        sys_user-equivalent row entirely - the participant record was the
        only authority and was free-form. The ServiceNow target replaces
        the entire participants-list-as-source-of-truth pattern with a
        single proper foreign-key Reference column on the case row,
        gaining four critical capabilities:
          * Referential integrity: only existing, active sys_user rows
            may be chosen (the platform's reference picker enforces this;
            the scripted REST submission endpoint may bypass at insert
            time only because Draft cases legitimately have no agent yet).
          * Membership semantics: the OOB `sys_user_grmember` join table
            provides direct user-group membership lookups via
            `gs.getUser().isMemberOf(groupSysId)`, which is what the
            "Assigned only" ACL condition and the agent-membership
            business rule both rely on. This was IMPOSSIBLE to express
            cleanly in ArkCase since the assignee was a String
            participantLdapId, not a foreign key.
          * Single source of truth: the same `sys_user` table that
            ServiceNow uses for all OOB authentication, role assignment,
            notification delivery, and dashboard scoping is now the
            canonical user backing case ownership.
          * Cascade safety: the platform's reference-deletion semantics
            (cascade rule, controlled by the `<reference_cascade_rule/>`
            element below - left empty for default "no cascade" behavior)
            prevent accidental orphaning of cases when a user is
            deactivated. ArkCase's String-username pattern silently
            broke when LDAP entries were renamed or removed.
      - The field name is `assigned_agent` (lowercase, snake_case; NOT
        `assignee`, NOT `assignedAgent`, NOT `assigneeLdapId`,
        NOT `assigned_to`) per AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim. This is an
        INTENTIONAL rename from ArkCase's derived `assignee*` getter
        family to align with the ServiceNow convention used by OOB
        tables (incident.assigned_to, sc_request.assigned_to,
        change_request.assigned_to all use `assigned_to` for the
        per-record-assignee column; AAP Section 0.5.7 chose
        `assigned_agent` as a near-identical variant that explicitly
        evokes the case-management persona "agent" rather than the
        generic "assigned_to" used by ITSM tables - this is the same
        rationale behind `assigned_group` vs the OOB `assignment_group`).
        The sibling x_casemgmt_case_task table also carries an assignee
        column (`assigned_to`, NOT `assigned_agent`, per AAP Section
        0.5.7) - the asymmetry is intentional: at the task level the
        OOB convention is preserved verbatim; at the case level the
        domain-specific "agent" terminology is used.
      - ArkCase's participantLdapId String had no explicit length cap
        (defaulting to the database-engine VARCHAR(255) for MySQL
        InnoDB). The ServiceNow target uses the standard 32-character
        Reference-field width to store the sys_id of the chosen
        sys_user row; the platform's auto-generated form picker, list
        view, and report builder all dereference to the user's display
        column (typically `name` or `user_name`) for human-readable
        display via the OOB sys_user dictionary's display=true column.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1, 0.7.2, 0.7.4):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: `<name>` resolves to `x_casemgmt_case`
        within the scoped application, and `<sys_scope>` / `<sys_package>`
        bind THIS dictionary record to the same scope by `source` attribute
        lookup. The `<reference>` element resolves to OOB `sys_user` by
        table name (NOT by sys_id), preserving zero-hardcoded-sys_id
        compliance. NO global-scope writes - the OOB `sys_user` table is
        REFERENCED but never modified.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: the `<sys_scope>`,
        `<sys_package>`, and `<reference>` text-node values resolve by
        scope source name and table name respectively, not by literal
        sys_id. The `<sys_id>` text-node value is THIS record's own
        deterministic primary key (MD5 of the canonical field identifier
        `x_casemgmt_case.assigned_agent`) and is NOT a reference to any
        other record. Per AAP Section 0.7.2 this scheme guarantees that
        a fresh PDI re-import of the Update Set produces byte-identical
        sys_id values, which is necessary for round-trip-verify
        (../scripts/round_trip_verify.md) zero-error preview.
      - The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used per AAP convention; ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the scope id is concrete in the XML before export.
      - mandatory=false at the dictionary level (CRITICAL: AAP Section
        0.5.7's "Optional; must be member of assigned_group" is BOTH a
        TRANSITION-LEVEL constraint enforced by the Flow Designer
        subflow at ../flows/sub_flows/validate_inprogress_transition.xml
        AND a RELATIONAL constraint enforced by the business rule at
        ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml,
        but is EXPLICITLY NOT a FIELD-LEVEL constraint enforced by the
        dictionary). Setting this to true would prevent Draft and Open
        cases from being saved without an agent, breaking AAP Section
        0.5.7's enumerated state list (Draft and Open are both allowed
        prior to In Progress) and AAP Section 0.5.1's portal-submission
        contract (anonymous external requesters submit cases that land
        in Draft with no agent or group set; an authenticated internal
        case_manager later picks up the Draft, assigns a group during
        Draft -> Open, and assigns an agent during Open -> In Progress).
      - read_only=false: case_manager users edit this field directly to
        assign the responsible agent. The field-level ACL in
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml enforces
        ROLE-BASED write access (case_manager always; case_agent only
        if currently assigned); the dictionary-level read_only flag
        remains false so the field is editable in principle by
        qualifying roles.
      - default_value (empty): no automatic agent assignment. The
        portal-submitted Draft case has no agent; the case_manager
        explicitly chooses an agent when promoting Open -> In Progress.
      - audit=false: per AAP Section 0.3.1 minimal-change clause and
        consistent with the sibling DateTime / Choice / String fields
        in this same dictionary set, only the `status` field carries
        audit=true (it is the most important field for state-machine
        forensics). Agent reassignment is logged through the standard
        sys_history_set / sys_audit infrastructure on demand but does
        not trigger the per-field audit overhead by default. The agent
        prompt's Phase 4 explicitly directs `audit=false` for this field.
      - max_length=32: the standard ServiceNow Reference-field width.
        The dictionary stores the 32-character lowercase-hex sys_id of
        the referenced sys_user row as the actual column value; the
        platform's auto-generated form picker, list view, and report
        builder all dereference to the user's display column (name)
        for human-readable display via the OOB sys_user dictionary's
        display=true column. The agent prompt's Phase 3 verbatim
        specifies "max_length=32 because reference fields store
        32-char sys_id values internally".
      - choice=0: this is a Reference field, NOT a Choice field. The
        sibling sys_choice_* records under ../choices/ apply only to
        the `type`, `status`, `priority`, `pending_reason`,
        `case_task.type`, `case_task.status`, and `case_party.party_type`
        columns - none are needed here.
      - choice_field, choice_table empty: same reason as choice=0 above.
      - reference=sys_user: OOB ServiceNow user table. AAP Section 0.5.7
        specifies this exact target table by name. No scoped wrapper or
        facade is needed; cases reference users directly across the
        scoped/global boundary, which ServiceNow permits for OOB tables
        (the reverse direction - global tables referencing scoped tables
        - would require a Cross-Scope Privilege record, but is not
        needed for this POC).
      - reference_cascade_rule (empty): default platform behavior, which
        is "do nothing on referenced-record deletion." If a user is
        deleted (a rare administrative operation), cases retain the
        orphaned reference; this is acceptable for the POC since user
        deletion is a global-admin-level operation already gated by
        global ACLs and is rare in practice. AAP does not specify a
        cascade rule.
      - reference_qual, reference_qual_condition (empty): no filter on
        which users may be selected. ANY active sys_user is eligible at
        the picker level. The membership constraint (must be a member
        of assigned_group) is enforced by the business rule and the
        flow subflow, NOT by a dictionary-level reference qualifier.
        This is by design per the agent prompt's Phase 3 ("the
        membership constraint is enforced by the business rule, not
        the dictionary") and Key Insight #5 ("Filtering the dropdown
        to 'only members of assigned_group' would require a dynamic
        reference qualifier referencing the OTHER field
        (assigned_group). For POC simplicity, we allow any sys_user to
        be selected; the business rule rejects invalid selections at
        save time."). A future enhancement could add a dynamic ref
        qual: `gs.getUser().isMemberOf(current.assigned_group)`.
      - use_reference_qualifier=simple: standard ServiceNow setting
        when no advanced (scripted) reference qualifier is in use.
      - dynamic_ref_qual (empty): no dynamic reference qualifier - see
        reference_qual rationale above.
      - reference_floor, reference_key, reference_type (empty): standard
        defaults for a basic table-to-table reference; no advanced
        reference semantics (typeahead override, reference floor table,
        document reference, etc.) are needed here.
      - element_reference=false: this is a TABLE reference, not an
        ELEMENT reference (which would point at a specific dictionary
        column on another table). AAP specifies a row-level reference
        target.
      - table_reference=false: this is NOT a "Document ID" / "Table"
        polymorphic reference (which is what `glide_var` style fields
        on the OOB task table use to reference any-table-any-row). It
        is a fixed-target reference to sys_user only.
      - text_index=false: Reference fields are not full-text-indexed.
        Searches by user are performed via GlideRecord addJoinQuery
        against sys_user on its sys_id column; full-text indexing of
        the 32-char sys_id has no value.
      - unique=false: a single user is correctly responsible for many
        cases (that is the entire point of agent-based case routing -
        a case_agent's "My Open Cases" workspace is meant to display
        many cases with the agent's sys_id in this column), so
        uniqueness on this column would be semantically wrong.
      - virtual=false: this is a stored column, not a calculated /
        virtual derivation. The actual sys_id of the chosen sys_user
        row is persisted on every record (in contrast to ArkCase's
        ON-THE-FLY derivation from participants).
      - spell_check=false: Reference fields hold a 32-char sys_id and
        the platform renders the dereferenced display value at view
        time; spell-check is meaningless for the persisted value and
        would be misapplied to the dereferenced human-name display.
      - No PII: the field stores a 32-char sys_id pointer to a user
        record; the user record itself stores categorical
        organizational identity (synthetic user_name, fabricated
        display name, fabricated email at the demo seed level only)
        per AAP Section 0.7.2 ("synthetic only"). The seed users at
        ../seed-data/users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_*.xml are
        fabricated synthetic accounts (one per role: case_manager,
        case_agent, case_viewer); no real names, real email addresses,
        or PII derived from the source ArkCase database are placed in
        this column at any point in the build.

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      - This record MUST load AFTER:
          * ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml (parent table; `<name>` here
            references the scoped table by name)
          * sys_user (OOB; always present on every PDI; never modified
            by this Update Set per AAP Section 0.3.2)
      - This record MUST load BEFORE the consumers that read or write
        the `assigned_agent` column:
          * ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml
            (uses this field as the chosen-agent input to the membership
            check; queries sys_user_grmember for
            (current.assigned_agent, current.assigned_group) and blocks
            save with a form-level error if the agent is NOT a member
            of the group)
          * ../flows/sub_flows/validate_inprogress_transition.xml (the
            Open -> In Progress gate; the subflow inspects
            current.assigned_agent and throws a blocking error if
            empty OR if the agent is not a group member)
          * ../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml (the parent flow
            for type=General Inquiry that calls
            validate_inprogress_transition)
          * ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml (the parent flow for
            type=Complaint that calls validate_inprogress_transition)
          * ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml
            (canTransitionToInProgress static method that reads
            current.assigned_agent and is called by both the flows and
            the business rules)
          * ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml
            (field-level ACL: write restricted to case_manager and the
            currently-assigned case_agent)
          * ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned.xml
            (table-level read ACL for case_agent; condition uses
            current.assigned_agent against gs.getUserID() to evaluate
            the first half of "Assigned only")
          * ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_agent_assigned.xml
            (table-level write ACL for case_agent; same condition as
            the read ACL above)
          * ../reports/x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml (list-style report
            filtered by `assigned_agent = javascript:gs.getUserID()` -
            the agent's daily workspace dashboard)
          * ../seed-data/users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_*.xml (the
            synthetic demo users - one per role - that the demo cases
            will reference; this dictionary entry must precede the seed
            users for the preview engine to reconcile the field schema)
          * ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_*.xml (synthetic demo
            cases that populate this field by lookup of the demo user's
            `user_name` attribute via the seed_demo_data.js script -
            never via hard-coded sys_id, per AAP Section 0.7.2 the
            no-hardcoded-sys_id constraint applies to flows, ACL
            conditions, scripts, seed data, UI Policies, UI Actions,
            Business Rules, and client scripts)
          * ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js (the idempotent seed script
            that calls `gs.getUserID('x_casemgmt_demo_agent')` or
            equivalent GlideRecord lookup by user `user_name` to resolve
            the sys_id at seed time, never via hard-coded literals)
-->
<record_update table="sys_dictionary">
